2. Data Exploration¶

1.Data Structure ('str(car_price)'):¶

'str()' is a R function which provides the framework of an object. It depicts the structure of the dataset 'car_price' in this case. This includes a description of the data types in each column as well as an overview of the first few observations in each column. It aids in comprehending the dataset's layout and content.

2.Statistics Summary (summary(car_price)):¶

In R, the 'summary()' function computes descriptive statistical data for each variable in the dataset. It provides numerical variables with mean, median, quartiles, and extremes (min, max), and categorical variables with counts of unique values. This summary aids in gaining an understanding of the numerical distributions and category variances in the dataset.

3.Examine for Missing Values (sum(is.na(car_price)):¶

is.na() is a function that checks a dataset for missing (NA) values. sum() is used to count the total number of missing values by adding the TRUE values (missing) returned by is.na(car_price). This stage is critical for finding any missing data in the dataset that will need to be dealt with during data preprocessing.

4.Check for Categorical Variables with Unique Values (table(car_price$fueltype)):¶

In R, the 'table()' function creates a frequency table of unique values for a given variable, in this instance the "fueltype" variable. It counts the number of times each unique value appears in the "fueltype" column. Recognizing unique values in categorical variables is critical for gaining insights into the dataset's diversity and distribution of categories.

3.Data Cleaning¶

1.Remove Rows with Missing Values : 'na.omit()' is a function in R that removes rows with any missing (NA) values from the dataset 'car_price'. The resulting dataset with no missing values is assigned to a new variable 'cp_info'.

2.Remove Columns with No Useful Information : This line removes a specific column named "car_ID" from the dataset 'cp_info'. 'names(cp_info)' retrieves the column names of the dataset 'cp_info'. '%in% c("car_ID")' checks if "car_ID" is present in the column names. '!(...)' negates the logical condition, so it selects columns that are not "car_ID". 'cp_info[, ...]' selects and retains only the columns that are not "car_ID" in the dataset.

3.Display the First 10 Rows : 'head()' function is used to display the first 10 rows of the dataset cp_info. This helps to preview the cleaned dataset and understand its structure after removing rows with missing values and the "car_ID" column.

In [ ]:
# Remove rows with missing values
cp_info <- na.omit(car_price)

# Remove columns with no useful information (here i am assuming 'car_ID' as an example)
cp_info <- cp_info[, !(names(cp_info) %in% c("car_ID"))]

4. Adaptation¶

  • In the dataset 'cp_info', a new column named "performance_ratio" is added.
  • For each row, divide the "horsepower" column by the "curbweight" column to get this column. It determines the horsepower to weight ratio, which shows a car's performance in terms of power relative to weight.
  • A new column called "avg_mpg" is added to the 'cp_info' dataset.
  • For each row, the "avg_mpg" column is computed by averaging the "citympg" and "highwaympg" columns. It shows a car's average miles per gallon (MPG), taking into account both city and highway driving conditions.
In [ ]:
# here we Created a new column 'performance_ratio' as horsepower to weight ratio
cp_info$performance_ratio <- cp_info$horsepower / cp_info$curbweight

# here we Created an aggregated column 'avg_mpg' as the average of citympg and highwaympg
cp_info$avg_mpg <- (cp_info$citympg + cp_info$highwaympg) / 2
head(cp_info, 10)

8. Simple Linear Regression¶

Here simple linear regression analysis performs five different predictor variables to predict the response variable price.

Model 1¶

In this horsepower is choosen as predictor variable and the ultimate aim is to check the price.

  • lm() function is used for linear regression, here price is regressed on horsepower using the data in the numerical columns.
  • summary() function provides a summary for the model's results like coefficients, R- squared value, p- values.
  • The coefficient for horsepower shows the estimated change in price for one unit increase in horsepower while keeping other variables constant.
  • R-squared value shows difference in price for one unit increase in horsepower. A higher R-squared value indicates a better fit.
  • p-value corelated with horsepower helps to estimate the statistical value of the predictor. A low p-value similar with horse power helps check out the statistical significance of the predictor of the price. *Illuminate the coefficient, R-squared value, and p-value to decide how well "horsepower" predicts "price."

Model 2¶

Here in the model 2 plot, we will be predicting the dependent variable price based on the independent variable enginesize.

  • In the residuals we get the difference between real and predicted values of the dependent variable. Here it also includes mean, standard error etc.
  • The major thing in the summary is coefficient that helps us to understand the regression model.
  • In the plot it displays Intercept as estimated coefficients and enginesize as independent variable.
  • And for every coefficient there are estimated value, std.error, t value etc.
  • So, the Intercept represents the estimated value of price when enginesize is zero(This might not have a meaningful interpretation in this context.)
  • The plot helps us to asses how the independent variable enginesize explains the dependent variable prics.

Model 3¶

In the model 3 plot we use curbweight as independent variable to predict the dependent variable price.

  • This provides the statistics related to residuals.
  • coefficient shows that estimated coefficents for the intercept and inndependent variable.(curbweight)
  • it fits the simple linear regression model with curbweight as the independent variable to predict the price. *The model is the good fit and the significance of the independent variable.

Model 4¶

In this model it creats the linear regression with the independent variable carlength to predict the dependent variable price,

  • Here the coefficient displays estimated coefficients for the intercept and the independent variable(carlength)
  • This is the great fit for the linear regression , carlength is the independent variable to predict price
  • It is a good fit and it provides the significance of the independent variable carlength.

Model 5¶

Here the linear regression is created by using the independent variable citympg which is city miles per gallon.

  • In this model the dependent variable is price based on the independent variable citympg.
  • summary provides the various statistics of the regression model.
  • The coefficient for citympg represents the estimated value change in price for one unit in citympg in this case it shows that how car fuel efficeincy affects the car orices.
  • The independent variable citympg explains the variation in dependent variable price.
  • This is a good fit and it shows the significance of the independent variable citympg.
In [ ]:
# Assuming your dataframe is named 'df'

# Model 1: Price ~ horsepower
model1 <- lm(price ~ horsepower, data = numerical_columns)
summary(model1)

# Model 2: Price ~ enginesize
model2 <- lm(price ~ enginesize, data = numerical_columns)
summary(model2)

# Model 3: Price ~ curbweight
model3 <- lm(price ~ curbweight, data = numerical_columns)
summary(model3)

# Model 4: Price ~ carlength
model4 <- lm(price ~ carlength, data = numerical_columns)
summary(model4)

# Model 5: Price ~ citympg
model5 <- lm(price ~ citympg, data = numerical_columns)
summary(model5)

9 Multiple Linear Regression:¶

  • Here in the multi_model , we are creating a multiple linear regression modelto pridict the dependent variable price based on independent variables like horsepower, enginesize, curbweight,carlenght and citympg. This model provides info regarding the model's coefficients, statistical significance, R-squared value etc.

  • In step wise regression, we are using the step() function. this is a very good technique for automatic variable selection. it removes or adds independent variables from the model based on the statistical data.This model describes about final selected model after the stepwise procedure including coefficients and statistical significance.

  • Next is the plotting Diagnostic plots for the best simple model. This plot has a 2x2 grid for the best linear regression model.

  • Plotting Diagnostic plots for the Multiple Linear Regression Model. This plot also sets 2x2 grid for multiple linear regression.

    # Interpretation and comparision in Multiple Linear Regression

  • The Multiple Linear Regression model has the mixed effect of five independent variables(horsepower, enginesize,curbweight,carlength, citympg) on predicting the dependent variable (price).

  • Stepwise regression (stepwise model) automatically selects a subset of independent variable.

  • Diagnostic plots(residual plots) are used to assess the validity of the models and check if any assumptions of assumptions of linear regressions are met.
  • The choice between the multiple regression model and a simple regression model depends on many factors.
  • A multiple linear regression model can capture more complex relationships but it may require more complex data and assumptions. simple linear regression models are easier to interpret but may not capture all relevent factors.

10. Project Report¶

This research revolves around a detailed study of a car pricing dataset, with the goal of improving our knowledge of the automotive market and assisting in informed business choices. Navigating the shifting automotive scene as a corporate leader necessitates precise and smart decision-making to survive in a highly competitive sector. The goal of this research is to use the automobile prices dataset to identify patterns and insights that can guide pricing strategies, market positioning, and, ultimately, company success.![download.png]

To begin our adventure, we carefully examined the dataset's structure, variables, and distributions. Key characteristics such as horsepower, curb weight, and fuel economy were of special importance since they frequently play key roles in affecting automobile costs. This first data investigation established the framework.

Following investigation, careful data cleaning was done to assure the dataset's quality and dependability. We removed inconsistencies, extraneous data, and values that were missing, resulting in a revised dataset. This clean dataset created the foundation for subsequent investigation, allowing for a more in-depth look at the factors influencing automobile costs.

In order to improve the dataset's insights, we included computed features such as 'performance_ratio' and 'avg_mpg'. These extra articles offered distinct viewpoints on a car's performance and energy efficiency, two essential considerations in a consumer's decision-making process. 'Performance_ratio' provided information on the horsepower to weight ratio, which reflects a car's performance, while 'avg_mpg' provided an average estimate of fuel economy, combining city and highway MPG statistics. The chosen response variable, automobile pricing, is extremely important in the automotive industry. A crucial component for allowing the best pricing techniques and market positioning is the accurate projection of automotive prices. In order to develop the most precise prediction model, we explored basic and multivariate linear regression models to forecast automobile prices based on numerous parameters.

In summary, this study provides priceless information that can influence pricing policies, product advancement, and market competitiveness. Utilizing these findings, we suggest adjusting pricing policies, placing a stronger emphasis on high-performance features, and giving fuel economy first priority in order to appeal to customer desires and stand out in the crowded car market.
